<section xml:id="sec-precalc-basics" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Arithmetic Basics</title>

  <p>
    Before starting calculus, it is important to be comfortable with basic arithmetic and algebraic rules.
    Many difficulties students experience in calculus come not from new ideas, but from small algebra mistakes.
    This section reviews core skills that will be used repeatedly throughout the course.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-whole-numbers-signs">
    <title>Signs</title>


    <p>
      We begin with rules involving negative signs.
      These rules appear constantly when simplifying expressions, computing slopes, and working with limits.
      Being fluent with sign changes will help prevent many common errors later on.
    </p>

       <principle xml:id="ax-sign-rules">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
-(-a) &amp; = &amp; a \\
(-a)b &amp; = &amp; -ab \\
(-a)(-b) &amp; = &amp; ab \\
a - b &amp; = &amp; a + (-b) \\
-(a - b) &amp; = &amp; b - a
\end{array}
</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Simplify <m>-(3 - 8)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          3 - 8 = -5, \qquad -(-5) = 5.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
  </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="ssec-fractions">
    <title>Fractions and Rational Expressions</title>

    <p>
      Fractions appear frequently in calculus, especially in limits and derivatives.
      Careful fraction manipulation is essential for simplifying expressions correctly.
    </p>


    <principle xml:id="ax-fraction-operations">
      <statement>
<p>
Assume <m>a, b, c, d</m> are real numbers with <m>b \neq 0</m> and <m>d \neq 0</m>.
</p>

<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\dfrac{a}{b} &amp; = &amp; a \cdot \dfrac{1}{b} \\[0.6em]
\dfrac{a}{b} \pm \dfrac{c}{d} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{ad \pm bc}{bd} \\[0.6em]
\dfrac{a}{b} \cdot \dfrac{c}{d} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{ac}{bd} \\[0.6em]
\dfrac{a/b}{d/c} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{ac}{bd}
\end{array}
</me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Simplify <m>\dfrac{2/x}{3/5}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \frac{2}{x} \cdot \frac{5}{3} = \frac{10}{3x}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

   <subsection xml:id="ssec-distributive">
    <title>Distributive Law and Common Errors</title>

    <p>
      Many fraction and sign errors come from misusing the distributive law.
      This law explains how multiplication interacts with addition and subtraction.
      Understanding when it applies, and when it does not, is critical for algebraic simplification.
    </p>

    <principle xml:id="ax-distributive-law">
      <statement>
<me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
a(b + c) &amp; = &amp; ab + ac \\[0.6em]
\dfrac{b + c}{a} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{b}{a} + \dfrac{c}{a}
\end{array}
</me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

 <example xml:id="ex-distributive-basic">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use the distributive law to simplify <m>3(x + 5)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
3(x + 5) &amp; = &amp; 3x + 3(5) \\
         &amp; = &amp; 3x + 15
\end{array}
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-distributive-fraction">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Simplify <m>\dfrac{x + 4}{2}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Apply the distributive law to the numerator:
      </p>
      <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\dfrac{x + 4}{2} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{x}{2} + \dfrac{4}{2} \\
                 &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{x}{2} + 2
\end{array}
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        The distributive law does not apply to square roots, powers, or denominators.
      </p>
      <me>
        \sqrt{x^2 + 9} \neq x + 3,
        \qquad
        (x + 3)^2 \neq x^2 + 9,
        \qquad
        \frac{1}{x + 3} \neq \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{3}.
      </me>
    </remark>









  </subsection>

 <subsection xml:id="ssec-exponents">
    <title>Powers and Rational Exponents</title>

    <p>
      Exponent rules allow us to rewrite and simplify expressions efficiently,
      which is especially important when computing limits and derivatives.
    </p>

   <principle xml:id="pr-exponent-laws">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Assume <m>a &gt; 0</m> and <m>m,n</m> are real numbers.
    </p>

<me>
\begin{array}{rcl|rcl}
a^n a^m &amp; = &amp; a^{n+m}, &amp;\hspace{1cm}
(a^n)^m &amp; = &amp; a^{nm} \\[0.6em]
(ab)^n &amp; = &amp; a^n b^n, &amp;
a^{-n} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{1}{a^n} \\[1em]
a^{1/n} &amp; = &amp; \sqrt[n]{a}, &amp;
a^{m/n} &amp; = &amp; \sqrt[n]{a^m} \\[0.6em]
a^{-m/n} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{1}{\sqrt[n]{a^m}}, &amp;
a^0 &amp; = &amp; 1
\end{array}
</me>
  </statement>
</principle>




    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Simplify <m>\dfrac{x^5}{x^2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \frac{x^5}{x^2} = x^{5-2} = x^3.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rewrite <m>x^{3/2}</m> using a radical.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          x^{3/2} = \sqrt{x^3}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-rationalizing">
    <title>Rationalizing the Denominator</title>


    <p>
      Finally, let's review rationalizing the denominator.    
      Rationalizing removes square roots from denominators. This technique appears often in limits.
    </p>


    <principle xml:id="thm-rationalize">
      <statement>
        <me>
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{a}} = \frac{\sqrt{a}}{a}.
        </me>
        <me>
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{a} + \sqrt{b}} =
          \frac{\sqrt{a} - \sqrt{b}}{a - b}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rationalize <m>\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{5}}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{5}} = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Rationalize <m>\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{x} + 2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{x} + 2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{x} - 2}{\sqrt{x} - 2}
          =
          \frac{\sqrt{x} - 2}{x - 4}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


</section>
